\begin{lemma}
If $\Gamma \prov A : \rtype$, then $\sem \Gamma, x : A^* \prov \sem A(x) : \rtype$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
Suppose we're working with
\[
\Gamma, y : B \prov C : \rtype
\over
\Gamma \prov (y : B) \to C : \rtype
\]
Then we need to show
\[ \sem \Gamma, x : ((y : B) \to C)^* \prov \sem {(y :B) \to C}(x) : \rtype\]
i.e.
\[ \sem \Gamma, x : (y : B^*) \to C^* \prov (y :B^*)(y' : \sem B(y)) \to \sem{C}(x\ y) : \rtype\]
so we need
\[ \sem \Gamma, x : (y : B^*) \to C^* \prov B^* : \rtype\]
\[ \sem \Gamma, x : (y : B^*) \to C^* \prov \sem B(y) : \rtype\]
\[ \sem \Gamma, x : (y : B^*) \to C^*, y :B^*, y' : \sem B(y) \prov  \sem{C}(x\ y) : \rtype\]
The first follows by induction on the other lemma. The second follows by induction on this lemma. For the third, we do induction on this lemma on
\[ \sem {\Gamma, y : B}, z : C^* \prov  \sem{C}(z) : \rtype\]
which gives us
\[ \sem {\Gamma}, y :B^*, y' : \sem B(y), z : C^* \prov  \sem{C}(z) : \rtype\]
then substitute $x\ y$ for $z$.
\cqed
\end{proof}


